<article class="single_blog_wrap  post-1083 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-getting-started-with-ios-app-development tag-hardware tt-blog-no-feature">
<div class="post_title">

<h2><a href="http://iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/hardware-needed-to-develop-ios-apps/" title="What Hardware Will You Need to Develop iOS Apps?">What Hardware Will You Need to Develop iOS Apps?</a></h2> 

</div><!-- END post_title -->

<div class="post_content">

<p><a href="http://i2.wp.com/iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/macbook_air.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1166 alignleft" style="border: 0px;" alt="macbook_air" src="http://i2.wp.com/iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/macbook_air.jpg?resize=300%2C222" data-recalc-dims="1" /></a>Before you can get going with iOS development there are a couple of hardware requirements that you will need to satisfy.  In this post, we’ll take a look at those requirements, discuss the various options for satisfying them and focus on the cheapest way to get started for those who want to develop iOS apps.<span id="more-1083"></span></p>
<h3></h3>
<h3>Minimum Requirements</h3>
<p>I’m not going to beat around the bush.  Bottom line is that if you want to get started with iOS application development your going to need (or at least have access to) a Mac and at a minimum it&#8217;s going to need to be Intel-based and running Snow Leopard (or more preferably Mountain Lion).</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">If you’re a PC owner, you’re out of luck I&#8217;m afraid.  The Xcode development tools are only available on OS X and there isn’t really a viable PC alternative at present.  I guess it’s a marketing choice on Apples behalf but for now if you want to join the world of iOS developers it&#8217;s a Mac or nothing.</p>
<p><a href="http://i1.wp.com/iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thunderbolt_display_mac_mini-e1365328925539.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1168 alignleft" alt="Mac Mini with Thunderbolt Display" src="http://i1.wp.com/iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/thunderbolt_display_mac_mini-e1365328925539.jpg?resize=200%2C189" data-recalc-dims="1" /></a></p>
<blockquote class="style5"><p>&#8220;The Mac Mini can be a great entry level solution but add a Thunderbolt Display and the costs start mounting.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<h3 style="text-align: left;">Development Hardware Options</h3>
<p class="wp-image-1168 " title="Mac Mini and Thunderbolt Display">So what does this mean if you haven’t already got a Mac and want to get started? Well, you have a few options.</p>
<p>The first is the <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009XCJ4QM/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B009XCJ4QM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009XCJ4QM/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B009XCJ4QM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'Mac Mini']);" title="Mac Mini"  target="_blank">Mac Mini</a>. At around £499 / $599 at the time of writing, this is a pretty good option if you want to get started and already have a display kicking around that you can hook it up to.  The down-side though is that if you haven’t, and you start adding the cost of one of <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B005DXS7DQ/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B005DXS7DQ&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B005DXS7DQ/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B005DXS7DQ&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'Apple’s Thunderbolt Displays']);" title="Thunderbolt Display"  target="_blank">Apple’s Thunderbolt Displays</a> into the mix, you’re looking at another £899 /  $999 at the time of writing and the costs are mounting pretty rapidly.</p>
<p>The next option then is the iMac.  A <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00AJGW95Y/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B00AJGW95Y&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00AJGW95Y/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B00AJGW95Y&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', '21.5-inch iMac']);" title="21.5-inch iMac"  target="_blank">21.5-inch iMac</a> is available from £1099 / $1299 and is a pretty good alternative to the <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009XCJ4QM/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B009XCJ4QM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009XCJ4QM/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B009XCJ4QM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'Mac Mini']);" title="Mac Mini"  target="_blank">Mac Mini</a> / <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B005DXS7DQ/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B005DXS7DQ&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B005DXS7DQ/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B005DXS7DQ&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'Thunderbolt Display']);" title="Thunderbolt Display"  target="_blank">Thunderbolt Display</a> combo and is around £300 / $300 cheaper.  It definitely gets around the problem of having to buy a separate screen and if you’re looking for a desktop solution this is probably your best bet.</p>
<dl class="wp-caption alignright" id="attachment_1164" style="width: 213px;">
<dt class="wp-caption-dt"></dt>
<dd class="wp-caption-dd">&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</dd>
</dl>
<p>For those looking for a more mobile alternative though (such as for coding in front of the TV &#8211; yes I admit I do that sometimes), you’ve really got a choice between the MacBook Air and the MacBook Pro.  An <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B005DY7A6U/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B005DY7A6U&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B005DY7A6U/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B005DY7A6U&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', '11 inch MacBook Air']);" title="11-inch Macbook Air"  target="_blank">11 inch MacBook Air</a> is available from around £849 / $999 and a <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B008BEYEL8/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B008BEYEL8&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B008BEYEL8/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B008BEYEL8&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', '13-inch MacBook Pro']);" title="13-inch Macbook Pro"  target="_blank">13-inch MacBook Pro</a> is a little more expensive at £999 / $1199.  My preference out of these would be the <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B008BEYEL8/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B008BEYEL8&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B008BEYEL8/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B008BEYEL8&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', '13-inch MacBook Pro']);" title="13-inch Macbook Pro"  target="_blank">13-inch MacBook Pro</a> though.  Both are viable alternatives but the one thing I have learnt is that Xcode <span style="text-decoration: underline;">loves</span> screen real-estate so where possible I’d go for the biggest screen you can afford.<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00AJGW95Y/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B00AJGW95Y&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00AJGW95Y/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=6738&amp;creativeASIN=B00AJGW95Y&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', '']);" style="color: #ea9629; text-decoration: underline; outline: #000000;"  target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" alt="Apple iMac" src="http://i0.wp.com/iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/2013-apple-imac-e1365329067145-254x300.jpg?resize=203%2C240" data-recalc-dims="1" /></a></p>
<blockquote class="style5"><p>&#8220;The iMac is perfect for those who don&#8217;t mind being bound to the desktop.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<h3>iOS Device Options</h3>
<p>In terms of the iOS Device side of things, the picture is a little more rosy.</p>
<p>When it comes to iOS devices, you <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>can</strong></span> start developing for iOS without owning an iOS device at all.</p>
<p>The Xcode development tools come with an iOS Simulator that allows you to simulate an iOS device right-there on your desktop.  This is great option for both novices and professionals alike but it does have it’s limitations and experience has proven that it is simply no substitute for being able to run your applications on a real iOS device.</p>
<p>With this in mind I&#8217;d recommend that you try to get your hands on an <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009ETBBJM/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B009ETBBJM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009ETBBJM/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B009ETBBJM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'iPhone']);" title="iPhone 5"  target="_blank">iPhone</a>, <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009A5EM3W/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B009A5EM3W&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B009A5EM3W/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B009A5EM3W&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'iPod Touch']);" title="iPod Touch"  target="_blank">iPod Touch</a>, <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00A37TCG8/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B00A37TCG8&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00A37TCG8/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B00A37TCG8&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'iPad']);" title="iPad"  target="_blank">iPad</a> or <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00A6QA4MM/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B00A6QA4MM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B00A6QA4MM/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1634&amp;creative=19450&amp;creativeASIN=B00A6QA4MM&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=iosdevetuto-21', 'iPad Mini']);" title="iPad Mini"  target="_blank">iPad Mini</a> as soon as you can.  In my opinion its really an essential purchase in the long-term, especially if you are going to develop applications for the App Store.  Depending on your needs though, you might not need the latest and greatest piece of Apple hardware and if your just getting started, my tip would be to keep an eye out on on <a href="http://www.ebay.com/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.ebay.com/', 'eBay']);" title="eBay"  target="_blank">eBay</a> or <a href="http://www.craigslist.org/about/sites" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.craigslist.org/about/sites', 'Craigslist']);" title="Craigslist"  target="_blank">Craigslist</a>, especially when Apple releases a new revision of their iOS hardware.  You’ll often find people selling off their devices as they upgrade and it can be a great way of picking up an inexpensive iOS Device to use.</p>
<p>Worst case though, if your budget really can&#8217;t stretch to an iOS device at the moment (especially if your having to splash out for a new Mac), don&#8217;t worry too much and please don&#8217;t be put off.  As I&#8217;ve mentioned previously, you can still get started with Objective-C and iOS Development with just an Intel-based Mac and the iOS Simulator and the important thing, as with many things, is overcoming inertia and getting started.<br />
<a href="http://i1.wp.com/iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/macbook_pro.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1167" alt="Apple Macbook Pro" src="http://i1.wp.com/iosdevelopmenttutorials.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/macbook_pro.jpg?resize=300%2C210" data-recalc-dims="1" /></a></p>
<blockquote class="style5"><p>&#8220;For a more mobile development platform, the Macbook Pro is probably your best bet but try to go for as much screen real-estate as you can afford.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>You probably won&#8217;t need an iOS device immediately anyway, especially if you&#8217;re new to the platform, so my approach would be to start learning Objective-C (this blog will help you with that) and in the mean time save up and buy an iOS device when your finances allow. Trust me, you&#8217;ll want one once you start writing apps of your own. There&#8217;s nothing quite like pulling out your iOS device and showing your friends your latest creation!</p>
<h3>Summary</h3>
<p>In this post we looked at the minimum hardware requirement for getting started with iOS development &#8211; an Intel-based Mac running Snow Leopard or later.   We looked at the options available for meeting this requirement and also took a look at the need to have an iOS Device upon which to run and test your software.  For many, the hardware entry barrier can seem high, but if you can stretch to it, you will have all the hardware you need to develop and distribute an app to millions of potential customers around the world.  Now isn&#8217;t that a price worth paying?</p>

</div><!-- END post_content -->

